\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will learn the basic concepts of turbulence modeling
 in computational fluid dynamics.
 We will concentrate on the methods with most practical usage, the Reynolds
 averaged Navier-Stokes (RANS) models with two transport equations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Great many different models exists, all with their advantages and weakness.
 As a rule of a thump: if you do not know what to do, use 
\begin_inset Formula $k-\omega$
\end_inset

-SST or k-
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 realizable with a wall function that works in most cases.
 See the documentation of your software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Disclaimer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turbulence modeling is a much studied subject that still lack a generally
 accepted solution.
 It is rather impossible to give generally accepted definitions.
 Different authors disagree on naming conventions and definitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this section attempts to give a general insight into most common
 turbulence models without going too much into the details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction to turbulence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All flows will become turbulence with sufficiently large Reynolds number,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Re}=\frac{UL}{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 In the low Reynolds number range, the viscosity effects are strong enough
 to dissipate the fluctuations arising from the non-linear nature of momentum
 advection.
 With higher Reynolds number, the momentum of the fluctuations becomes too
 strong for the viscosity to dissipate.
 This creates eddies in the flow.
 The eddies interact with the mean flow and with each other creating a highly
 non-linear and chaotic behavior.
 This chaos is generally described as turbulence.
 Note, however, that there is no generally accepted definition for turbulence
 and the word might be used differently in different contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our purposes it is convenient to divide the instantaneous velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 into mean 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and fluctuating 
\begin_inset Formula $u'$
\end_inset

 parts as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u=U+u'\label{eq:Reynold decomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this is called Reynolds decomposition.
 See Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Reynolds-decomposition"

\end_inset

.
 Other quantities, such as temperature, have a similar fluctuation and are
 similarly decomposes.
\end_layout

